#heading(outlined: false)[Abstract]

This thesis investigated how SOLWEIG-derived urban microclimate data can be transformed and integrated into a fully open-source, scalable pedestrian routing tool that supports thermally conscious mobility decisions. Using a design-based research approach, a modular workflow was developed for a case-study area in Rotterdam under high-heat conditions. The component of the workflow can prepare the required input data, run SOLWEIG_GPU to generate hourly UTCI outputs and efficiently sample them onto an OpenStreetMap-derived pedestrian network as edge-level thermal-comfort attributes. These attributes are then incorporated into a modified, state-aware weighted Dijkstra algorithm that balances route length with dynamic heat-exposure penalties and user-defined preferences and these routes can be visualized in a locally deployed web-ui. The results show that thermally conscious routes can reduce modelled UTCI exposure compared with the shortest path, particularly during hotter hours, while requiring only limited additional walking distance. The thesis demonstrates that scalable microclimate-informed routing depends not only on the routing algorithm itself, but also on data structures, file formats, network representation, and modular software design.